        curl -sL -o tslib.tar.gz \
          https://codeload.github.com/jehangiramjad/tslib/tar.gz/3e50bc1fbe0178bf2c1b21b2ce9fd0f0ca2d5f76

    It extracts into benchmarks/reference/.cache/tslib/ (gitignored) and runs
    the genuine RobustSyntheticControl fit from there.

Dependencies: numpy, pandas, scikit-learn.

Compatibility note: tslib targets Python 2.7 / early 3, and
src/synthcontrol/syntheticControl.py mixes tabs and spaces in its predict() /
getControl() methods, which raises TabError on import under Python 3. RSC's fit
path does not use those methods -- RobustSyntheticControl.fit delegates straight
to src/models/tsSVDModel.py::SVDModel.fit (N=1, includePastDataOnly=False,
SVD/numpy). clone_tslib.py therefore imports the clean SVDModel and constructs +
fits it exactly as the RobustSyntheticControl constructor does
(build_rsc_weights). The RSC algorithm itself is the upstream source, unmodified.

No modifications are made to the reference source.

Convention note (see benchmarks/cases/pcr_rsc_ref.py)
-----------------------------------------------------
HSVT+OLS is deterministic given the retained rank k, but tslib and mlsynth
de-noise slightly differently: tslib forms the donor-subspace projection from an
SVD of the *stacked donor+treated* pre-matrix (the treated row participates in
the rank-k truncation), whereas mlsynth's PCR (Amjad-Shah-Shen 2018 convention,
the deliberate choice in mlsynth.utils.clustersc_helpers.pcr.pipeline) de-noises
the donor pre-matrix *alone*. Both then OLS the treated pre-series onto the
de-noised donors; neither constrains the weights or adds an intercept. Stacking
the treated row rotates the rank-k donor subspace marginally, so the two learned
weight vectors agree to ~5e-4 and the ATTs to ~0.04 packs/capita at k=3 -- the
genuine numerical gap of the differing de-noising convention, not a bug.
